       "   'merged_at': None},\n",
       "  'body': 'closes #64184\\n\\n## Summary\\n\\n`pd.to_numeric` lost precision for integer-like strings with leading zeros once the result was forced to `float64`, e.g. `\"000000000010084566\"` became `10084560.0` instead of `10084566.0`.\\n\\nThe root cause is in the `precise_xstrtod` fallback (`tokenizer.c`): it accumulates up to `max_digits = 17` digits into the mantissa and pushes the rest into the exponent, but **leading zeros were counted against that 17-digit budget**. For an 18-character zero-padded value, the budget was exhausted on zeros and the final significant digit was turned into a `×10` instead of a digit.\\n\\nThe fix skips leading zeros so they no longer consume the digit budget (with a `seen_digit` flag so legitimately-zero inputs like `\"0\"` still parse rather than tripping the \"no digits\" guard).\\n\\n## Current state of the reported symptom\\n\\nThe user-facing `to_numeric` symptom was already fixed incidentally by the fast_float refactor GH-64432 (which routes `to_numeric`/`floatify` through fast_float), but **without a targeted regression test**. The same latent bug still lived in the fallback path, which is reachable via `read_csv(..., thousands=...)`:\\n\\n```python\\npd.read_csv(io.StringIO(\"x\\\\n000000000010084566.0\\\\n1.5\\\\n\"), thousands=\",\")[\"x\"][0]\\n# before: 10084560.0   after: 10084566.0\\n```\\n\\n## Tests\\n\\n| Path | Test | Guards |\\n|---|---|---|\\n| `read_csv(thousands=)` fallback | `test_precise_xstrtod_leading_zeros` | the latent bug this fix closes |\\n| `to_numeric` (fast_float) | `test_leading_zeros_no_precision_loss[_coerce]` | regression of the symptom GH-64432 fixed |\\n\\nRelated precision work: GH-64357, GH-64395.\\n\\n🤖 Generated with [Claude Code](https://claude.com/claude-code)\\n',\n",
