       "   'merged_at': None},\n",
       "  'body': 'closes #51866\\n\\nSetting a value with `DataFrame.at` / `Series.at` using a non-scalar indexer (a boolean mask, list, array, or slice) raised a message that blamed the *value*:\\n\\n```python\\ndf.at[df[\"b\"] == 6, \"b\"] = np.nan\\n# InvalidIndexError: You can only assign a scalar value not a <class \\'float\\'>\\n```\\n\\nThis is misleading — `np.nan` *is* a scalar; the real problem is the indexer. Every path that reaches this handler involves a non-scalar (or, for `MultiIndex`, non-hashable) row/column label — a plain missing scalar label raises `KeyError` and falls back to `.loc` — so the message can safely point at the indexer in all cases. It now reads:\\n\\n```\\nInvalidIndexError: At based indexing can only have scalar indexers; use .loc instead\\n```\\n\\nmirroring the existing `.iat` message (`\"iAt based indexing can only have integer indexers\"`).\\n\\nThe `Series.at` path previously caught only `KeyError`, so a mask dumped the raw indexer repr; it now raises the same clear error. This also tidies up the message added in GH-48890 for the whole-row case (GH-48729, e.g. `df.at[\"a\"] = [123, 15]`), which now gets the same `.loc` pointer.\\n\\n🤖 Generated with [Claude Code](https://claude.com/claude-code)',\n",
