       "  'body': \"closes #50373\\n\\n`DataFrame.replace(..., 1)` / `Series.replace(Ellipsis, 1)` raised `TypeError: Expecting 'to_replace' to be either a scalar, array-like, dict or None, got invalid type 'ellipsis'`, even though the dict-like (`replace({Ellipsis: 1})`), list-like (`replace([...], 1)`), and value (`replace(1, ...)`) forms all already accept `Ellipsis`.\\n\\nThe rejection comes from the `is_scalar(to_replace) or is_re_compilable(...) or is_list_like(...)` guard. `is_scalar(Ellipsis)` is deliberately `False` (it's grouped with `slice(None)` as an indexing token, and indexing code relies on that), so the scalar path special-cases `Ellipsis` rather than touching `is_scalar`.\\n\\n**This is a borderline call, flagging for a maintainer decision.** The argument *for* is purely consistency with the dict/list/value forms that already work, plus the fact that `replace` is value-equality replacement and `... == ...` is well-defined / `...` is storable in object arrays. The argument *against*: `...` is an indexing token (we reject `slice(None)` here), the use case is contrived, and `to_replace is Ellipsis` is an admitted special-case wart. Happy to instead close as wontfix, or pursue rejecting `...` everywhere for symmetry with `slice`, if reviewers prefer.\",\n",
