       "  'body': 'closes #63936\\nxref GH-64024 (temporary xfail, reverted here)\\n\\nWith ``infer_string=False``, ``dtype=\"str\"`` resolves to the numpy ``\\'<U\\'`` dtype, so ``DataFrame(obj, dtype=\"str\")`` goes through the object/numpy path in ``ndarray_to_mgr`` (not the ``StringDtype`` EA path the issue title suggests). That path realizes the cast via ``sanitize_array`` → ``_try_cast`` → ``lib.ensure_string_array(copy=False)``, which returns a **view** of the source when it already holds strings.\\n\\n``refs`` was gated on ``astype_is_view(values.dtype, dtype)``, and ``astype_is_view(object, \\'<U\\')`` is ``False`` (correct for ``.astype``, which copies). So refs were dropped even though memory was shared, leaving ``_has_no_reference(0)`` ``True``. This is a real copy-on-write violation — mutating the resulting DataFrame corrupted the source ``Series``/``Index``:\\n\\n```python\\nwith pd.option_context(\"infer_string\", False):\\n    obj = Series([\"a\", \"b\"], dtype=\"str\")\\n    df = DataFrame(obj, dtype=\"str\")\\n    df.iloc[0, 0] = \"ZZZ\"\\n    # before: obj == [\"ZZZ\", \"b\"]  (corrupted)\\n    # after:  obj == [\"a\", \"b\"]    (unchanged)\\n```\\n\\n## Fix\\n\\nIn ``ndarray_to_mgr``, hold onto the source\\'s references and attach them when the realized block **actually** shares memory with the source (checked via ``np.shares_memory`` after ``sanitize_array``). This is precise: a non-string object source (e.g. ``[1, 2]``) genuinely copies in ``ensure_string_array``, so refs correctly stay unset there.\\n\\nThe ``StringDtype`` EA path (``infer_string=True``) was already correct, so no change is needed in ``_form_blocks``.\\n\\nAlso re-enables the ``\"str\"`` case in ``test_dataframe_from_series_or_index`` that GH-64024 temporarily xfailed.',\n",
