       "   'merged_at': None},\n",
       "  'body': 'closes #59823\\n\\nWhen resampling `on=` a pyarrow-backed datetime/duration column, the result index lost its name:\\n\\n```python\\ndf = pd.DataFrame({\"date\": ..., \"metric\": ...}).astype({\"date\": \"timestamp[ns][pyarrow]\"})\\ndf.resample(\"D\", on=\"date\").sum().index.name  # None, should be \"date\"\\n```\\n\\n`TimeGrouper._set_grouper` rebuilds the Arrow time axis as a plain `Index(...)` for binning but dropped `ax.name`, so the binner labels (and the final index) came out unnamed.\\n\\nThe prior fix for GH-61222 (#61229) added a band-aid in `_wrap_result` (`result.index.name = self.obj.index.name`) that only works when resampling on the *index* — for `on=` a column, `self.obj.index` is the default RangeIndex with no name, so it actively clobbered the correct name. This PR fixes the root cause by carrying `ax.name` through in `_set_grouper` and removes the now-redundant band-aid; `astype` to the Arrow dtype preserves the name on its own.\\n\\n- [x] closes #59823\\n- [x] Tests added and passed\\n- [x] All code checks passed\\n- [x] Added an entry in the latest `doc/source/whatsnew/v3.1.0.rst`',\n",
